      dek: `Not all festivals are equal, and understanding the rough hierarchy — from the world-famous to the tiny local — is essential to building a smart strategy. Each tier offers something different, costs something different, and fits a different film. Here's how the pyramid works.`,
      body: `<p>The festival world is a rough pyramid. At the top sit a small number of internationally famous festivals whose selection can transform a film's fortunes; below them, a large band of respected specialty and mid-tier festivals that offer real value; and at the base, an enormous number of smaller regional, local, and niche festivals. Understanding this hierarchy matters because <strong>the tier of a festival determines what a selection is worth to you</strong> — in prestige, in press, in industry access, and in cost and competition to get in — and a good strategy usually mixes tiers deliberately rather than aiming only at the top or settling only for the bottom. It's worth saying plainly: this hierarchy is real but informal and imperfect, "prestige" is partly subjective and shifts over time, and a festival's <em>fit</em> for your specific film can matter more than its raw ranking. Still, knowing the tiers lets you plan a run that balances ambition with realism. Let me walk the pyramid.</p>

<h2>The tiers, top to bottom</h2>

<p>Roughly, festivals fall into these bands:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Top-tier / A-list.</b> A handful of world-famous international festivals. Selection here can launch a film and a career, brings major press and industry attention, and is extremely competitive. Getting in is life-changing and very hard.</li>
  <li><b>Major specialty &amp; Oscar-qualifying.</b> Highly respected festivals — including genre and category leaders and those that can qualify a short for awards consideration — that carry real prestige, strong press, and buyer presence without being the very top.</li>
  <li><b>Strong mid-tier &amp; regional flagships.</b> Well-regarded festivals with good audiences, some press, and industry attendance. Very valuable for building a run, and more attainable than the top for most indie films.</li>
  <li><b>Niche &amp; genre festivals.</b> Festivals devoted to a specific genre, theme, format, or community (horror, documentary, LGBTQ+, sci-fi, student, etc.). For the right film, a niche festival can be more valuable than a bigger general one — reaching exactly your audience.</li>
  <li><b>Regional &amp; local.</b> Smaller community festivals. Less prestige and press, but easier to get into, often welcoming, good for laurels, audience, and a screening — and sometimes a genuinely warm experience.</li>
  <li><b>Be wary of "pay-to-play" mills.</b> Some outfits exist mainly to collect entry fees and hand out meaningless "awards" with little real audience or value. Learn to spot and avoid these; a laurel from a junk festival adds nothing.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Using the tiers strategically</h2>

<p>Knowing the pyramid, the strategic move is to <strong>build a run that mixes tiers on purpose, matched to your film's realistic level and your goals.</strong> A common smart shape: reach for a few top or major festivals as "dream" targets (long odds, but the upside is huge and you protect your premiere for them), anchor your run in strong mid-tier and well-chosen niche festivals where your film has a real shot and the value is high, and include some accessible regional or genre festivals to guarantee screenings, laurels, and audience. This portfolio approach means you're neither betting everything on impossible-to-get top festivals nor wasting your whole run on tiny ones — you're spreading across tiers to balance ambition and results. Two crucial nuances. First, <em>fit can beat prestige</em>: a mid-tier festival that's perfect for your film's genre and audience may do more for you than a bigger general festival where your film gets lost — a horror film at a beloved genre festival can outshine the same film buried in a huge general lineup, so don't chase raw ranking over relevance. Second, <em>be honest about your film's level</em>: aiming a modest first film only at the world's top three festivals is a recipe for an expensive, deflating run of rejections, while a realistic mix produces actual selections and momentum — ambition is good, delusion is costly. And protect yourself from the pay-to-play trap: a real festival has an actual audience, a physical (or genuine online) event, a curated program, and a reputation; an "award" from an outfit that accepts everyone and exists to bank fees is worthless and can even make your kit look naive, so vet festivals before you spend. The tiers aren't a rigid ranking to obey; they're a map to plan with, so you can aim high where it's worth it, anchor where you'll succeed, and avoid where it's a waste. With the hierarchy understood, the next chapter turns all this foundation into an actual plan — building your submission strategy.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Build a run that mixes tiers on purpose — a few dream reaches, an anchor of strong mid-tier and niche festivals where you have a real shot, and accessible ones to guarantee screenings. Fit can beat prestige; delusion is costly; and a junk-festival laurel is worthless.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Two tier lessons shaped how I plan. First, I once aimed a small personal film only at the very top festivals, got a wall of rejections, and nearly gave up — then a mentor pointed me to the right mid-tier and niche festivals for that film, where it thrived. Fit and realism beat pure ambition. Second, I got seduced early by an official-looking festival that accepted my film instantly and handed me an "award" — turned out to be a fee-collecting mill with no real audience, and the laurel meant nothing. Now I vet every festival: real event, real program, real reputation. Plan across tiers, aim where you can actually land, and never mistake a pay-to-play badge for a credential.</p>
</div>`,
