      dek: `This is where foundation becomes plan. Before you spend a dollar on submissions, you build a strategy: clear goals, a tiered target list, a budget for fees, and a timeline mapped to the calendar. A written plan is what turns the circuit from a money pit into a campaign.`,
      body: `<p>Everything in Module 1 has been building to this: an actual plan. A festival strategy is a written document — goals, targets, budget, timeline — that turns the abstract "I'll submit to festivals" into a deliberate campaign. Without it, you default to the expensive lottery: submitting to whatever's open, spending on impulse, burning your premiere by accident, and running out of money before the festivals that matter. With it, every submission is a considered move toward a defined goal. The good news is that building the plan is straightforward now that you understand why festivals matter (Ch1), how the circuit flows (Ch2), and how the tiers work (Ch3). This chapter assembles those foundations into a strategy you can execute, and the Core Craft module then teaches the tactics (choosing, submitting, getting in) that fill it in. Think of this as writing your festival business plan before you start spending.</p>

<h2>The pieces of a festival strategy</h2>

<p>A real submission strategy includes:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Clear goals.</b> Define what a successful run means for this film — a prestige premiere, a sale, a genre reputation, an audience, a career calling card. Your goal drives every other choice.</li>
  <li><b>A tiered target list.</b> A curated list of festivals across tiers (a few reaches, a solid anchor of realistic and niche fits, some accessible picks), each chosen for fit — not a giant list of everything.</li>
  <li><b>A budget.</b> Entry fees add up fast, so set a total budget and allocate it deliberately across your targets. Decide how much you can spend before you start, and don't blow it on impulse submissions.</li>
  <li><b>A timeline.</b> Map submissions to the calendar and deadlines: which festivals to hit at early-bird pricing, when your premiere target's deadline falls, and how the sequence unfolds over the year.</li>
  <li><b>Premiere protection.</b> Decide where you want to premiere and hold the film for it — don't submit anywhere that would burn that premiere before your top target has decided.</li>
  <li><b>A tracking system.</b> A simple way to record each festival's deadline, fee, status, and result, so you always know where things stand and what's next. This is the operational backbone of the campaign.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Write the plan, then work it</h2>

<p>The single biggest mistake in festival submissions is <strong>spending money reactively instead of following a plan</strong> — seeing a deadline, feeling urgency, submitting on impulse, and repeating until the budget's gone with little to show. A written strategy inoculates you against this. Once you've defined your goal, built a fit-based target list across tiers, set a budget, and mapped a timeline, submitting becomes executing a plan rather than reacting to FOMO. A few disciplines make the plan actually work. First, <em>budget realistically and protect it</em>: fees are meaningful money and it's easy to overspend, so decide your total up front, prioritize your best-fit targets, and use early-bird deadlines and fee waivers (more on those later) to stretch it. Second, <em>be selective, not exhaustive</em>: a focused list of well-chosen festivals beats a sprawling one — you'll get better results and spend less by submitting thoughtfully to the right festivals than by carpet-bombing every festival that exists. Third, <em>protect your premiere in the plan</em>: build the sequence so your film debuts where you want it, because premiere status is a lever you can only use once. Fourth, <em>plan the timeline around the calendar</em>: since deadlines run months ahead and festivals are seasonal, a good plan spans a year or more and places the film deliberately — patience beats panic. And fifth, <em>keep it flexible</em>: a strategy is a living plan, so as results come in (an acceptance here, a rejection there, a new laurel), you adjust — doubling down where there's traction, pivoting where there isn't. The filmmakers who have great festival runs almost always have a plan they wrote before submitting and worked steadily; the ones who flame out almost always submitted reactively without one. So do the unglamorous work now: write your goals, build your list, set your budget, map your timeline, and set up tracking. With a strategy in hand, Module 2 fills in the craft — starting with the most important tactical skill, choosing the right festivals for your specific film.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The biggest festival mistake is spending money reactively instead of following a plan. Write your goals, target list, budget, and timeline before you submit a single film — then every submission is a move, not an impulse.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My reactive-submitting era ended the day I actually wrote a festival plan. For my next film I sat down first: goal (a genre reputation and a sale), a tiered list of maybe fifteen well-fit festivals, a hard budget, and a timeline mapped to deadlines with my premiere protected. Then I just worked the plan — submitting on schedule, at early-bird prices, tracking every result. That run cost less than my chaotic first one and did far more, because every dollar had a purpose. Writing the plan felt like a chore next to the excitement of submitting, but it was the difference between a campaign and a spending spree. Plan first. Always.</p>
</div>`,
