      dek: `With thousands of festivals out there, the single most important tactical skill is picking the right ones for <em>your</em> film. Genre, length, subject, level, and logistics all matter. Choose well and your submissions convert; choose blindly and you burn money on festivals that were never going to want your film.`,
      body: `<p>Choosing festivals is where strategy meets reality, and it's the skill that most determines whether your run succeeds. The core principle is <strong>fit</strong>: a festival is right for your film when your film is the kind of thing they program and their audience wants to see. Submitting a raunchy horror short to a family-values festival, or a two-hour experimental feature to a festival that only screens narrative shorts, is money set on fire — not because your film is bad, but because it doesn't <em>fit</em>. Programmers are curating a specific event for a specific audience, and they select films that serve it. So the job is to research each festival — what they program, who attends, past selections, submission categories — and only submit where your film genuinely belongs, at a tier you can realistically reach. Do this well and your acceptance rate climbs and your budget goes further; do it blindly and you'll rack up rejections that had nothing to do with quality. Let me lay out the factors that determine fit.</p>

<h2>What determines fit</h2>

<p>Match your film to festivals on these dimensions:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Genre &amp; subject.</b> Does the festival program your kind of film? A genre or theme festival (horror, doc, comedy, LGBTQ+, environmental, etc.) can be a perfect home; a general festival may or may not lean toward your type. Study their past lineups.</li>
  <li><b>Format &amp; length.</b> Shorts vs. features, and specific runtime limits, matter enormously — many festivals only take one, or cap length. Check categories and rules; submitting the wrong format is an instant no.</li>
  <li><b>Level &amp; competitiveness.</b> Match the tier to your film's realistic level (Ch3). Include reaches, but anchor in festivals where you have a genuine shot.</li>
  <li><b>Audience &amp; region.</b> Who attends, and where? A regional festival near your story's setting, or a festival whose audience is your target audience, can be worth more than a bigger, less relevant one.</li>
  <li><b>Past selections.</b> Look at films they've programmed before — if they resemble yours in tone, scale, or subject, that's strong evidence of fit. Festivals have personalities; find the ones that share yours.</li>
  <li><b>Practical factors.</b> Deadlines, fees, premiere requirements, whether it's competition or showcase, and value for money. A festival can fit creatively but still be wrong for your budget or timeline.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Research beats guessing</h2>

<p>The habit that separates smart submitters from money-burners is simple: <strong>research each festival before you submit, instead of guessing from the name.</strong> Spend a little time on each target — read their about page and mission, scan past programs, note their categories and rules, check who attends and what they seem to value — and you'll quickly sense whether your film belongs. This is not glamorous, but it's the highest-return work in the whole submission process, because every dollar you spend on a festival that was never going to want your film is a dollar wasted, and every dollar spent on a genuine fit is an investment with real odds. A few tactics sharpen this. First, <em>let your film's identity guide you</em>: honestly characterize your film — its genre, tone, length, subject, audience — and seek festivals built for exactly that, because a niche festival that's a bullseye for your film often beats a bigger general one where it's a marginal fit. Second, <em>learn from similar films</em>: find films like yours that had good festival runs and see where they played — those festivals are strong candidates for you, and this is one of the fastest ways to build a great target list. Third, <em>use the platforms and lists wisely</em>: submission platforms let you filter by category, deadline, and fee, and there are curated lists and communities that flag reputable, well-fitting festivals — but always verify a festival is real and relevant before submitting. Fourth, <em>weigh cost against value</em>: a festival that fits perfectly but costs a lot and offers little for your specific goals may still not make the cut, so judge each target on fit <em>and</em> return. And fifth, <em>don't submit out of ego or FOMO</em>: the temptation to throw entries at famous festivals your film has no realistic shot at, just to say you tried, drains budgets — reach deliberately, not desperately. Choosing well is genuinely the difference between a run that builds and one that just bleeds money. Put in the research, match your film to festivals that want it, and your submissions become investments instead of gambles. With your target list chosen, the next chapter covers the mechanics — how to actually submit a film to festivals.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A festival is right for your film when your film is what they program and their audience wants to see. Research each target before you submit — every dollar on a festival that was never going to want your film is a dollar burned.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Early on I submitted my dark, weird horror short to a bunch of prestigious general festivals because they were prestigious — and got nothing but rejections. Then I actually researched: I found genre and horror festivals whose past lineups were full of films exactly like mine, and I looked up where a couple of similar shorts I admired had played. I submitted to <em>those</em>, and suddenly I was getting in — to festivals with audiences who loved my kind of film. The film hadn't changed; my targeting had. Fit beats prestige, and thirty minutes of research per festival is the best money-saving, acceptance-boosting habit in the whole game.</p>
</div>`,
