      dek: `The mechanics of submitting are simpler than they used to be — most festivals run through online platforms now. But the details matter: deadline tiers, entry fees, fee waivers, and getting your submission right. Here's how to submit smoothly and keep costs down.`,
      body: `<p>Submitting a film to festivals is far easier than it once was, because most festivals now accept entries through online submission platforms — <strong>FilmFreeway</strong> being by far the dominant one, with others existing too. You create a project page for your film (with your screener link, poster, stills, synopsis, and details), then submit to festivals from that single profile, paying the entry fee per submission. This centralization is a gift: you build your film's page once and can submit to dozens of festivals from it, and the platforms let you search and filter festivals by category, deadline, and fee. But smooth, affordable submitting still depends on understanding a few things — the deadline tiers that affect price, how entry fees work and add up, the fee waivers that can save you real money, and getting the submission itself right so it's not disqualified on a technicality. Let me cover the mechanics.</p>

<h2>The mechanics of submitting</h2>

<p>What to know to submit well:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The submission platform &amp; project page.</b> Set up a complete project page (screener, poster, stills, synopsis, credits, contact) once. A clean, complete page makes every submission easier and looks professional to programmers.</li>
  <li><b>Deadline tiers.</b> Most festivals price by deadline: earlybird (cheapest), regular, late, and extended (priciest). Submitting earlier saves money — and since some festivals fill slots as they go, it can help your odds too.</li>
  <li><b>Entry fees.</b> Fees vary widely (from modest to steep, higher for bigger festivals and features). They add up fast across a run, which is why your budget and target list from earlier chapters matter so much.</li>
  <li><b>Fee waivers.</b> Festivals sometimes issue waiver codes that reduce or eliminate the fee — via newsletters, filmmaker communities, platform promotions, or on request. Hunting for legit waivers can meaningfully stretch your budget.</li>
  <li><b>Your screener.</b> A reliable, high-quality private online screener (with a password, captioned if needed) that plays smoothly. Programmers watch a lot of films; a glitchy or hard-to-access screener hurts you.</li>
  <li><b>Match the rules exactly.</b> Right category, correct length, eligibility (completion date, premiere requirements, region), and any required fields. A submission that breaks a rule gets rejected regardless of quality — read each festival's rules.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Submit early, submit clean, save where you can</h2>

<p>A few disciplines make the submission process cheaper and more effective. First and most practical: <strong>submit at the earliest deadline you can.</strong> Earlybird pricing is genuinely cheaper, and because you've planned your run in advance (Ch4), you should rarely be scrambling to hit a late, expensive deadline — plan to submit early, both to save money and because some festivals review and fill on a rolling basis. Second, <strong>hunt for fee waivers, but stay legitimate.</strong> Entry fees are the biggest cost of a festival run, and legit waivers (from festival newsletters, filmmaker organizations, platform promos, or politely asking a festival) can cut that cost substantially — it's worth the effort to find them, though never try to game the system dishonestly. Third, <strong>make your screener bulletproof.</strong> Programmers watch hundreds of submissions, often at speed; if your screener won't load, buffers, or is annoying to access, you've hurt yourself before they've judged a frame, so use a reliable host, a stable private link with a simple password, good quality, and captions where useful, and test it yourself on multiple devices. Fourth, <strong>read and follow each festival's rules precisely.</strong> Eligibility rules — completion date windows, premiere requirements, length caps, category definitions, regional restrictions — disqualify more submissions than people realize, and a rejection on a technicality is pure wasted money, so check every festival's rules and make sure your film qualifies and you're submitting in the right category before you pay. Fifth, <strong>keep your project page complete and current</strong>, because it's both your submission and, often, the first thing a programmer sees — a full, tidy page with a strong poster and synopsis makes a better impression than a bare one. And sixth, <strong>track every submission</strong> (festival, deadline, fee paid, status, result) so you never double-submit, miss a deadline, or lose the thread of your campaign. None of this is difficult, but attending to it turns submitting from a leaky, expensive fumble into an efficient process. With clean submissions going out, the next chapter looks at the package itself from the programmer's side — what they're actually judging when your submission lands.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Submit at the earliest (cheapest) deadline, hunt for legitimate fee waivers, make your screener bulletproof, and follow each festival's rules exactly — a rejection on a technicality is pure wasted money.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Two submission lessons cost me money before I learned them. First, I used to submit at the last minute at "extended" deadline prices — the most expensive tier — out of disorganization; once I planned ahead and hit earlybird deadlines, my per-festival cost dropped a lot for the exact same festivals. Second, I got a technical rejection because my film was two minutes over a festival's runtime cap, which I hadn't checked — pure wasted fee. Now I plan to submit early, chase legit fee waivers, keep a rock-solid screener, and read every festival's eligibility rules before paying. Submitting is easy; submitting <em>smart</em> saves real money and avoids dumb rejections.</p>
</div>`,
