      dek: `When your submission lands, a programmer forms an impression from more than just the film — the title, the poster, the synopsis, the first minutes of your screener all shape whether they lean in. This chapter is about the package they judge, and making yours work in your favor.`,
      body: `<p>Programmers and screeners at festivals watch an enormous volume of submissions, often under time pressure, and while the film itself is what ultimately decides selection, the <strong>whole package</strong> around it shapes how they approach your film before and while they watch. Your title, your poster thumbnail, your synopsis, the professionalism of your project page, and — critically — the opening minutes of your screener all form impressions that can make a tired programmer lean in with interest or brace for another mediocre entry. This isn't about tricking anyone; a great package can't save a weak film. But a strong package ensures your film gets a fair, engaged watch rather than a distracted, skeptical one, and in a stack of hundreds of submissions, that engagement matters. Much of this connects to the EPK skills from the neighboring course — the synopsis, poster, and stills you built there are exactly what a festival submission uses. Here's what programmers judge and how to make it work for you.</p>

<h2>What programmers see</h2>

<p>Your submission package includes:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The title.</b> A strong, memorable, tone-appropriate title creates a first impression before anything else. It's small, but it colors expectations — make it good.</li>
  <li><b>The poster / thumbnail.</b> Programmers scan project pages and see your key art small. A professional, striking poster signals a serious film; an amateur one signals the opposite (see the EPK course on getting this right).</li>
  <li><b>The synopsis &amp; logline.</b> A tight, intriguing synopsis that sells the film without spoiling it frames the watch. Programmers read a lot of dull summaries — a compelling one earns goodwill.</li>
  <li><b>The screener — especially the first minutes.</b> The opening is disproportionately important. Programmers can't watch every film to the end at leisure, so a strong, confident opening that signals quality and intent is crucial to keep them engaged.</li>
  <li><b>A complete, professional project page.</b> Full details, good materials, correct credits, working links. Completeness and polish read as "this filmmaker is serious," which primes a more generous watch.</li>
  <li><b>Fees &amp; format compliance.</b> Paid correctly, right category, meets the rules. Handled from the last chapter, but it's part of the package landing cleanly.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The film is the point — but the package earns the watch</h2>

<p>The honest framing here is important, so let me be clear: <strong>the film is what gets you selected, not clever packaging</strong> — a beautiful poster and a great logline will not get a weak film into a good festival, and you should never mistake presentation for substance. What a strong package <em>does</em> is ensure your film gets the engaged, fair watch it deserves, which is genuinely valuable when a programmer is on their two-hundredth submission of the week and inclined to make quick judgments. Two things deserve emphasis. First, <strong>the opening minutes of your film carry outsized weight.</strong> Realistically, overwhelmed programmers don't always watch every submission fully or with full attention, and a slow, unconfident, or amateurish opening can lose them before your film gets going, while a strong open that immediately signals craft and intent buys you their engagement — so make sure your film starts as well as it can, and consider that the first few minutes may be the most-scrutinized part of your whole film in this context. Second, <strong>professionalism throughout the package sets the frame.</strong> A complete project page with a real poster, a sharp synopsis, correct credits, and a flawless screener tells the programmer, before they even watch, that this is a serious filmmaker — and that predisposition subtly shapes how they receive the film. The opposite — a bare page, a frame-grab poster, typos, a glitchy screener — primes skepticism. So build your submission package with the same care you'd give a pitch: strong title, professional poster and stills, a compelling synopsis, a complete page, and above all a film that opens confidently and plays flawlessly. Do that, and every festival gives your film its best possible chance to be seen as it truly is. Getting selected is still ultimately about the film — but the package makes sure the film is actually seen. With a strong submission out, the next chapter goes deeper into the selection process itself and how to improve your real odds of getting in.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The film is what gets you selected, not clever packaging — but a strong package earns your film an engaged, fair watch in a stack of hundreds. And the opening minutes may be the most scrutinized part of your whole film.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>A programmer friend once described their reality: hundreds of submissions, watched fast, often judged in the first few minutes. A confident opening bought a film their full attention; a slow or amateurish one got a skim. That reframed everything for me. I stopped treating the submission as "upload film, pay fee" and started treating it as a package: a real poster, a sharp synopsis, a complete page, and above all a film that <em>opens</em> strong. I even recut an opening once specifically because I knew those first minutes were where it'd be judged. The film still has to deliver — but making sure it's met with an engaged watch, not a distracted skim, genuinely changed my results.</p>
</div>`,
