      time: "8 min",
      moduleKey: "apply",
      kicker: "Putting It to Work",
      seoTitle: "Premiere Status & Timing Your Festival Run | Filmmaker Genius",
      seoDesc: "Film festival premiere status explained — world, international, and regional premieres, why they matter, and how to time your festival run to use them well. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 9 of Film Festival Strategy.",
      dek: `"Premiere status" sounds like insider jargon, but it's one of the most important strategic levers you have — and one you can only use once. Where and when your film first plays affects what bigger festivals will consider it for. Here's how premieres work and how to time your run around them.`,
      body: `<p>A "premiere" in festival terms means the first time your film screens in a given territory or context, and many festivals — especially bigger ones — care a lot about premiere status because programming a premiere is more prestigious and exclusive for them. There's a hierarchy: a <strong>world premiere</strong> (the film's first public screening anywhere), an <strong>international premiere</strong> (first outside its home country), a <strong>national/country premiere</strong>, and <strong>regional/local premieres</strong> (first in a state, city, etc.). The key strategic fact is that <strong>you can only have one world premiere</strong>, and once your film has played somewhere, it may no longer qualify for the premiere requirements of a festival that wanted it to debut with them. Some top festivals will only take world or international premieres; play a small festival first, and you can accidentally disqualify your film from a bigger one's consideration. This is why premiere status has come up repeatedly as something to <em>protect</em> in your planning — it's a one-time resource that shapes what's possible, and mismanaging it is one of the most common and costly festival-strategy mistakes.</p>

<h2>How premieres and timing work</h2>

<p>The moving parts:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The premiere hierarchy.</b> World (first anywhere) &gt; international (first outside home country) &gt; national &gt; regional/local. Bigger, more prestigious festivals often require higher premiere status.</li>
  <li><b>You get one world premiere.</b> It's a single, unrepeatable asset. Where you spend it sets the tone for your whole run, so it's worth protecting for the best festival you can realistically land.</li>
  <li><b>Playing early can disqualify you later.</b> Screening at a small festival (or even some public online showings) can cost you premiere eligibility at a bigger festival that required a premiere — the classic trap.</li>
  <li><b>Check each festival's premiere requirements.</b> Festivals state what premiere status they require (or prefer). Some demand a world/international premiere; many don't care. Know before you submit or accept.</li>
  <li><b>Sequencing your run.</b> Plan the order: hold the film for your premiere target's decision, then cascade to festivals with looser (or regional) premiere requirements, using regional-premiere slots at later festivals.</li>
  <li><b>Timing to the calendar.</b> Align your premiere target's deadline and event date with your film's completion, so you're not forced to premiere somewhere lesser just because you finished at an awkward point in the year.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Protect the premiere, don't over-obsess</h2>

<p>The practical strategy is a balance. On one hand, <strong>protect your premiere deliberately</strong>: if there's a bigger or better-fit festival you're genuinely aiming for that requires a world or international premiere, don't burn that status by accepting an earlier screening elsewhere before you hear from them — this means, in your planning, holding the film and sequencing your submissions so your premiere target gets first shot. Filmmakers lose big opportunities every year by carelessly playing a minor festival (or posting the film publicly online) and only then discovering it disqualified them from a major one. So build premiere protection into your timeline from the start, know each target's premiere requirements, and don't accept a screening that would spend your premiere on something lesser than your real goal. On the other hand, <strong>don't let premiere anxiety paralyze your run.</strong> Premiere status matters most for the top tier of festivals; the majority of festivals in a typical indie run don't require a world premiere, and once your premiere is placed (or once you've realistically concluded the top premiere-requiring festivals aren't happening for this film), you should freely play the many festivals that use regional or local premieres or don't care at all. The mistake in the other direction is holding your film hostage indefinitely, chasing a top premiere that isn't going to come, while your run stalls and the film ages — at some point, a great regional premiere and an active run beats an unspent world premiere sitting on a shelf. So the rule of thumb: <em>protect your premiere for your realistic best target, give that target its shot, and then let the film travel freely</em>. And a crucial practical warning that ties to earlier courses: be careful about <strong>public online screenings and even some public showings</strong> before your premiere, because they can count as "premiering" the film and quietly burn your status — so if you're protecting a premiere, keep the film private (festival screeners are fine; public posting is not) until that premiere happens. Handle premiere status well and it's a powerful lever that can lift your whole run; handle it carelessly and you can foreclose your best opportunities before you even realize what you've done. With your premiere placed and your run sequenced, the next chapter is about what to do once you're actually <em>in</em> — working the festival itself.</p>

<div class="pullquote">You get exactly one world premiere, and playing somewhere early can quietly disqualify you from a bigger festival that wanted your debut. Protect your premiere for your realistic best target — then let the film travel freely.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I learned premiere status the hard way: I let a short play a tiny local festival because it was fun and nearby — and then discovered it had disqualified the film from a much bigger festival that only took premieres. A one-time asset, spent on nothing, by accident. Since then I plan premieres deliberately: I identify my realistic best premiere target, keep the film private (no public online posting) until that festival decides, then cascade to festivals with regional or no premiere requirements. But I also don't hold films hostage forever chasing an impossible top premiere — once my real target has had its shot, I let the film travel. Protect the premiere; don't imprison the film.</p>
</div>`,
