      seoDesc: "How to work a film festival — showing up, networking, meeting industry, and making the most of your screening once your film is selected. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 10 of Film Festival Strategy.",
      dek: `Getting selected is the beginning, not the end. What you do at the festival — whether you show up, how you connect with people, how you use your screening — determines how much value you actually extract from that hard-won slot. Here's how to work a festival like a pro, without being sleazy about it.`,
      body: `<p>A festival selection is a door opening, but you have to walk through it. Too many filmmakers get accepted, feel proud, and then treat the festival passively — maybe not even attending — and let a valuable opportunity mostly go to waste. The filmmakers who get the most from festivals treat each one as an active event to <strong>show up for, engage with, and use</strong>: they attend when they can, they connect with audiences, fellow filmmakers, programmers, and industry, and they make the most of their screening moment. This isn't about being a slick operator or working the room in a gross way — most valuable festival connections come from being genuinely present, curious, and generous, not from aggressive self-promotion. It's about recognizing that a festival is a rare gathering of exactly the people who can help your film and your career, and that <em>being there and being human</em> is how the real value — relationships, word of mouth, opportunities — actually flows. Let me cover how to work a festival well.</p>

<h2>How to make the most of your selection</h2>

<p>When your film is in a festival:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Attend if you possibly can.</b> Showing up in person is where the value is — audiences, filmmakers, programmers, and industry are all there. If travel is impossible, engage remotely as much as the festival allows, but in-person presence is the gold.</li>
  <li><b>Promote your screening.</b> Help fill your screening — invite people, post about it, use your EPK and socials. A packed, engaged screening feels better, and festivals notice filmmakers who bring an audience.</li>
  <li><b>Be present at the screening &amp; Q&amp;A.</b> Introduce your film, do the Q&amp;A well, talk to audience members after. This is your moment to connect the film to real people and leave an impression.</li>
  <li><b>Connect genuinely with other filmmakers.</b> Your peers are your community, your future collaborators, and often your best source of advice, contacts, and support. These relationships are frequently the most lasting value of a festival.</li>
  <li><b>Meet programmers &amp; industry, respectfully.</b> Say thank you to the programmers who selected you; be open to conversations with any industry present (sales, distributors, press). Be interested and easy, not pushy.</li>
  <li><b>Follow up afterward.</b> Connect with the people you met, send a thank-you, keep the relationships warm. The festival ends but the network you built continues — the follow-up is where connections become relationships.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Presence and generosity beat hustle</h2>

<p>The mindset that makes working a festival feel good rather than gross is to remember that <strong>the most valuable festival connections come from being genuinely present and generous, not from aggressive networking.</strong> Nobody enjoys the person aggressively pitching their film at every stranger; people warm to the filmmaker who's curious about others' work, supportive of their peers, gracious to the festival staff, and simply <em>there</em> — at screenings, at the mixers, in the lobby conversations. Those human connections are where opportunities quietly originate: a fellow filmmaker introduces you to a programmer at another festival, an audience member turns out to work at a company, a peer becomes a collaborator on your next film, a programmer remembers you fondly and champions your next submission. So show up, be interested, be kind, and let the relationships form naturally — that generosity is both more pleasant and more effective than hustle. A few practical notes. If you truly can't attend (cost, distance), don't treat the selection as worthless — you still get the laurel, the credibility, and often the screening; engage however the festival allows and promote it, but understand you're leaving some value on the table, so prioritize attending the festivals that matter most to your goals. Bring materials — cards, your EPK link, a way for people to find your film — so a good conversation can lead somewhere. Do your Q&amp;A well: it's a real chance to make an impression, so be prepared, warm, and concise, and connect the film to the audience. And crucially, <em>follow up</em>: the biggest waste in festival networking is meeting great people and never reaching out again, so within a few days, message the people you connected with, thank the programmers, and keep the relationships alive — that follow-up is what converts a nice festival chat into a lasting professional relationship. Festivals are, at their heart, gatherings of your industry and community, and the value of a selection is only partly the screening itself — the rest is who you meet and what grows from it. Show up, be generous, connect genuinely, and follow up, and each festival becomes a node in a network that carries your career forward. With your run underway and connections forming, the next chapter covers how selections and screenings turn into momentum through awards and laurels.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A selection is a door opening — you have to walk through it. The most valuable festival connections come from being genuinely present and generous, not from aggressive networking. Show up, be kind, and follow up.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My most valuable festival didn't come from my screening at all — it came from the lobby. I'd shown up nervous, not planning to "network," and just ended up talking films with other filmmakers, being curious about their work, helping where I could. One of them later introduced me to a programmer at a bigger festival; another became a collaborator; an audience member from my Q&amp;A turned out to work somewhere useful and reached out months later. None of it was hustle — it was just being present and generous and then following up. The filmmakers who skip attending, or who work the room like sharks, miss the real thing. Show up, be human, and keep in touch.</p>
</div>`,
