      dek: `The festival circuit isn't the destination — it's the on-ramp. Everything you built on the circuit, from laurels to relationships to momentum, exists to help your film reach an audience. Here's how to turn a festival run into distribution and get your film seen.`,
      body: `<p>Here's the thing that took me years to internalize: <strong>the festival circuit is a means, not an end.</strong> The laurels, the awards, the packed screenings, the relationships — all of it exists to serve one goal, which is getting your film in front of an audience and, ideally, earning something back for the people who made it. A festival run that never converts into distribution has done part of its job (validation, exposure, relationships) but missed the biggest part: reach. So the final and most important move in festival strategy is to treat the circuit as the on-ramp to distribution, and to actively use everything you built there — the credibility of your selections, the talking points of your awards, the audience proof, the industry contacts you met — as leverage to get your film sold, streamed, or otherwise distributed to real viewers. This is where a festival run pays off or peters out, and it's where you should be thinking from the very beginning. Let me walk through how the circuit converts into distribution.</p>

<h2>How a festival run becomes distribution</h2>

<p>Turning circuit success into reach:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Your festival run is your sales pitch.</b> Selections, awards, laurels, and audience response are exactly the evidence distributors and sales agents look for — your run is the proof that your film works and has an audience.</li>
  <li><b>Meet buyers and sales agents on the circuit.</b> The industry attends festivals to find films. The relationships you build with sales agents, distributors, and acquisitions people during your run are the direct path to a deal.</li>
  <li><b>Know your distribution options.</b> Traditional distributor, sales agent, streaming platforms, self-distribution — festival success gives you leverage across all of them; choose the path that fits your film and goals.</li>
  <li><b>Momentum has a shelf life.</b> The window when your film is "hot" from a great run doesn't last forever — move on distribution conversations while the momentum and press are fresh.</li>
  <li><b>Your EPK and materials do the closing.</b> When a buyer is interested, your press kit, screener, and laurel-laden materials are what they evaluate — have them ready and polished (see the EPK course).</li>
  <li><b>Even without a deal, distribute.</b> If no distributor bites, festival credibility still powers self-distribution — streaming, VOD, screenings — so your film reaches an audience either way.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Playing the long game — and finishing this one</h2>

<p>The filmmakers who convert festival runs into distribution are the ones who plan for it from the start and stay active at the finish. From the beginning, you should be thinking about who your film is for and how it might reach them, so that when your run generates momentum, you're ready to capitalize — with materials prepared, a sense of your distribution options, and an openness to the industry conversations that festivals make possible. During the run, treat every buyer, sales agent, and acquisitions person you meet as part of your distribution path, and remember that <em>your festival run is your sales pitch</em>: the selections and awards and audience response are precisely the evidence that convinces a distributor your film is worth taking on. When interest comes, move — <strong>momentum has a shelf life</strong>, and the window when your film is fresh and talked-about is when deals happen, so don't let a promising conversation cool while you sit on it. And if the traditional deal doesn't materialize, don't treat that as the end of the road: festival credibility is real leverage for self-distribution too, so use your laurels and press to drive your own streaming release, VOD, community screenings, or whatever path gets your film to its audience. The goal was never the trophy or even the selection — it was reach, and there's more than one way to get there. That's the whole arc of festival strategy, and it's the arc of this course: you learned why festivals matter and how the circuit and its tiers work, you built a submission strategy and learned to choose festivals and submit well, you navigated premiere status and worked your screenings, you turned laurels and awards into momentum, and now you convert that momentum into getting your film seen. Play it thoughtfully, from the first submission to the final deal, and the festival circuit becomes exactly what it should be — the on-ramp that carries your film out into the world. You've finished the course. Now go get your film in front of an audience.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The festival circuit is a means, not an end. Your festival run is your sales pitch, and momentum has a shelf life — the goal was never the trophy, it was reach. Use everything you built to get your film seen.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My biggest festival regret wasn't a rejection — it was a deal I let slip. I had a good run, a couple of laurels, an audience award, and a sales agent who reached out warm. I was tired, I was slow to respond, I "wanted to think about it," and by the time I got serious the momentum had cooled and the interest faded. The next film, I treated the whole run as a sales campaign from day one: materials ready, options mapped, and when a conversation got warm I moved on it fast. That film got distributed. The circuit was never the point — reach was. Build the run, then use it, and don't let a fresh moment go stale.</p>
</div>`,
